\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Proof By Induction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These proofs work best when we have a claim that holds over some countable
 set (usually the natural numbers or a subset of the natural numbers).
 Start by taking the lowest number the claim holds for.
 Prove the claim for this number.
 This is called the base case.
 Now, prove that if the claim holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, it must also hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

.
 This is the induction step.
 If both the base case and induction step hold, so must the original claim.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove the formula for the triangle numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{n}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}i=\frac{n\left(n+1\right)}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
pf
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First start with the base case when 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{1}i=1=\frac{2}{2}=\frac{1\left(1+1\right)}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that the base case holds, we will perform the induction step.
 Suppose the formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{n}$
\end_inset

 holds whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq n\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{k}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}i=\frac{k\left(k+1\right)}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we add 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 to both sides, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}i+\left(k+1\right)=\frac{k\left(k+1\right)}{2}+\left(k+1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k+1}i=\frac{k\left(k+1\right)}{2}+\left(k+1\right)=\left(k+1\right)\left(\frac{k}{2}+1\right)=\left(k+1\right)\left(\frac{k}{2}+\frac{2}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k+1}i=\frac{\left(k+1\right)\left(k+2\right)}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we expected.
 As both the base case and induction step holds, we have proven our claim
 by induction.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

