 Thus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3n+5=3\left(2k+1\right)+5=6k+3+5=6k+8=2\left(3k+4\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as 
\begin_inset Formula $3k+4\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+5$
\end_inset

 is even.
 To show 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 must be odd if 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+5$
\end_inset

 is even, we will show the contrapositive holds.
 The contrapositive states if 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even, 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+5$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is even.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=2k
\]

\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{Z}.$
\end_inset

Thus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3n+5=3\left(2k\right)+5=6k+4+1=2\left(3k+2\right)+1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as 
\begin_inset Formula $3k+2\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3n+5$
\end_inset

 is odd.
 As we have proven the contrapositive, we know that the original statement
 also holds.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, a proof by contradiction helps.
 Suppose there are finitely many primes.
 We will number them 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2},\dots,p_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i}|\prod_{k=1}^{n}p_{k}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in other words, each prime number divides the product of all of the primes.
 As a prime number must be larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{i}\not|\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(p_{k}\right)+1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As there are no primes in our list that divide 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(p_{k}\right)+1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(p_{k}\right)+1$
\end_inset

 contains no prime factors! This is a contradiction as every integer greater
 than one contains a unique prime factorization.
 Thus to avoid contradiction there must be infinitely many prime numbers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will do a proof by contradiction using the same reasoning as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 irrationality proof.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{p}$
\end_inset

 were rational.
 Then there would exist 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 st 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 is fully reduced.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{p}=\frac{a}{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\frac{a^{2}}{b^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pb^{2}=a^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 are integers, this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, as is 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=pc$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pb^{2}=\left(pc\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pb^{2}=p^{2}c^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b^{2}=pc^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}$
\end_inset

 is also divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is as well.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 are both divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, this contradicts our earlier assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

 is fully simplified! Thus to avoid contradiction, we must allow 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 to be irrational.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
6)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 digit number of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x=a_{n}a_{n-1}\dots a_{0}$
\end_inset

 where each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1,2,\dots,9\right\} $
\end_inset

, and each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents a digit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}\left(10\right)^{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For convenience, we will also define the sum of the digits as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x-s=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}\left(10\right)^{i}-\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}=\sum_{i=0}^{n}a_{i}\left(\left(10\right)^{i}-1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(10\right)^{i}-1=999\dots999$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $9|\left(10\right)^{i}-1$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 As such, 
\begin_inset Formula $9|a_{i}\left(\left(10\right)^{i}-1\right)$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $9|x-s$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x}{9}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{s}{9}$
\end_inset

 have the same remainder.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $9|x$
\end_inset

, then the remainder is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $9|s$
\end_inset

.
 And similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $9|s$
\end_inset

, then the remainder is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $9|x$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
7)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{a}{b}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\frac{c}{d}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c,d\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $b,d\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p+q=\frac{a}{b}+\frac{c}{d}=\frac{ad}{bd}+\frac{bc}{bd}=\frac{ab+bc}{bd}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as 
\begin_inset Formula $ab+bc,bd\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bd\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p-q=\frac{a}{b}-\frac{c}{d}=\frac{ad}{bd}-\frac{bc}{bd}=\frac{ab-bc}{bd}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
as 
\begin_inset Formula $ab-bc,bd\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bd\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p-q\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 If we add the restriction that 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $c\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p}{q}=\frac{\left(\frac{a}{b}\right)}{\left(\frac{c}{d}\right)}=\frac{a}{b}*\frac{d}{c}=\frac{ad}{bc}
\]

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $ad,bc\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bc\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p}{q}\in\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\end_layout

